### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:To locate a choker not located in a jewelry box or boutique where would you go? Choices:  A: jewelry store B: neck C: jewlery box D: jewelry box E: boutique<n>Output:		We are looking for the word "Jewelry," so our answer is C.<n><n>Input: What is 7*9*12*?<n>Output: 10*9*9 =1779<n><n>### Instruction:<n>Given a series of questions, the student must answer the given questions in the input file, then write a print statement in which the student writes out the total number of times an answer was given.<n>The output file, which takes the input, should be as follows:<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The only baggage the woman checked was a drawstring bag, where was she heading with it? Choices:  A: garbage can B: military C: jewelry store D: safe E: airport<n>Output:		She was heading somewhere with her bag.  We don't know where that is.<n>A: She probably headed somewhere with garbage and garbage cans are for garbage.<n>B: I think military has something to do with guns and maybe this woman didn't want anyone finding her bag with her military stuff.<n>C: It could be where she was going is a jewelry store but she would put her bag in a safe and put it out in the open.<n>D: I think airport because the airport is where you would head for getting there if you were going somewhere.<n>E: This was probably her last choice in places she could go based on her bag.<n>Since we know she was coming from somewhere and we don't know where she was going, we can't choose any options.<n><n>Input: What is two plus two plus two?<n>Output: Two plus two plus two = <<2+2+2=6>>6<n><n>Input: My roommate and I each have a dollar.  We pay a quarter for two hours of internet access. How much internet will we buy?<n>Output: We each have a single dollar.  We would have to pay a quarter for $1*2 = <<1*2=2>>2 hours of net access.<n>Since we each have $1 we will each have $1*2 = $<<1*2=2$>>2<n>Since the internet costs $1/2=$<<1/2=0.5>>0.5<n>We will have to buy $2*.5=$<<2*0.5=1>>1 hour<n>So the final answer for the number of hours will be 1<n><n>Input:The candy bar has 3 chocolate squares, each has chocolate on one side, the other three sides are all peanut butter.  You are only allowed to eat the chocolate side of each square.  How many pieces of candy bars can you eat?<n>Output: The bar has a total of 3*3 = <<3*3=9>>9 squares<n>You would want to eat the chocolatel sides which give you 3*9 =<<3*9=27>>27 chocolate sides<n>But the three other sides are all peanuts butter which give you 6=<<6=6>>6 more peanut butter

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. This happens because water molecules have a stronger attraction to other water molecules than to cellulose molecules found in paper fibers.<n><n>D: A page can flatten, curl, or be crumpled by squeezing.  Paper has two directions: width and length and there are different ways to change this such as: pressing down to flatten (increase compression) or pulling the paper by its edge (decompression).<n><n>E: Paper crumples when you press the paper in a specific way<n><n>Input: How do you solve the following equation? What you have to take? Choices:  (X+2)(X-5)=X5<n>Output: The equation can't be solved without more information as is.  To try and calculate it, just guess the answer and enter it in the calculator and plug it in, but nothing will happen.<n><n>To calculate the answer, you have to solve two equations:<n><n>X+2=X-5<n><n>X+2-X-5=X-5-X+2<n><n>X+2+1=-5-2+2<n><n>You cancel out the X's by subtracting them out of each side.<n><n><n><n>X+2 - X+2 = -5 - 2 + 2<n><n>X+0 = -5+2<n><n>X = -7<n><n>So X+2 =X-5 is solved where X is -7 (X+2=0,X-5=7).<n>To solve the other equation, you add x to each side:<n><n>X+4=X-3<n><n>X+4-X-3=X-3-X+4<n><n>X+4+1=4+1<n><n>So you end up with: X + 4 = 5<n><n>But, X + 4 = X,

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:They decided to hash things out over drinks, after enough booze they were able to get close on a few things and what? Choices:  A: reach tentative agreement B: suicide C: examine thing D: commit murder E: stay in bed<n>Output:		They decide to examine things(D) and that is why they (D) could not (C) come to an agreement<n>So the final answer Is D<n><n>Input:Whats 2.6987 to the 657th power? Choices:  L: 999 Bottom Line C: 2.6999 G: 1 C: 1 C: L: N<n>Output: 999(L) because 2.69 has many more 1's than 10.001 and G is the only choice if you want everything to be a single digit.<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the instruction by using the computer code below<n><n>Input:How many digits are in one thousand(1000)? <n>Output:1 000 <n><n>Input:How do you write 1000 in the 999th position?<n>Output:012345678901011 <n><n>Input:Write the digits of pi until the first three digits are 3.14!<n>Output:314! <n><n>Input:What is the maximum value of x, where x ^2=0.001?<n>Output: 0.00021565 <n><n>Input: Find the 9990-th digit in 1049099, rounded to the nearest integer.<n>Output: 39<n><n>Input: 77<n>Output: 7<n><n>Input: 11<n>Output: 11<n><n>Input: 855<n>Output: 0484<n><n>Input:463<n>Output:0821<n><n>### Instructions:Answer the following multiple-choice items. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Though she made the cut years ago, its figurative scars would never what? Choices:  A: joining B: put together C: stitch D: heal E: paste<n>Output:		Though she made the cut years agough, its figurative scares would never D: heal.<n>If you ever watch CSI: New York you have most likely heard the expression cut too close to the bone.<n>If I am cut, I expect the wound to eventually heal.  However if this had happened figuratively, I expect the negative effect to remain for an extended period of time.

If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:If you want to make a big splash in a river with a rock, from where should you throw it? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where are people likely to find food? Choices:  A: opera B: supermarket C: building D: conference E: apartment<n>Output:		A: opera B:supermarket C: conference D:building E: apartment<n><n>### Instruction:<n><n>```<n>	if (answer = "opera" && answer = "supermarket") {<n>		answer = "building";<n>	}<n>```<n><n>### Instructions:<n>* Write the code to have the computer output each answer one at a time and have the human choose which one was correct.<n>* When both are sure that they both have chosen the correct answer, enter the 4th choice as the correct answer.<n>* If the computer is the one who makes the correct choice 3 out of 4 times, then the human is given a strike.<n>* If the human gets 3 strikes, the computer is declared the victor.<n><n>### Instructuon:<n><n>```<n>if (answer < 4) {<n>	computer = true;<n>	human = false;<n>} else {<n>	computer= false;<n>	human = true;<n>}<n>```<n><n><n>

Choices:  A: towed B: accidents C: driving D: getting tired E: ticket<n>Output:		<n>A) The correct choice that is not a valid option is towed<n>B) It would be more valid if you include other forms of possible accidents due to the car being not moved during required time<n>C) Getting tired can only happens during the driving. The car still needs to move during the required time<n>D) Getting tired can only happened during the driving. The correct choice is getting tired during the driving<n>E) The question states the possibility to receive a ticket. Ticket is a valid term that covers the question
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What do people in the same family often share? Choices:  A: brown hair B: names C: two eyes D: will E: brains<n>Output:		People in the same family often have the same genes and parents which determines their characteristics. These traits include body type, hair color, eye color, and personality traits like emotion and intelligence. The same family can also share the need for food, clothing, and shelter (and the same home with the same chores, etc.).<n>So the answer is E<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:James chose to not to print the cards, because he wanted to be more personal. His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What could a balalaika be needed for? You can use the expressions x or x plus one. <n>Output: x + (x+1) = <<x+x+1>>x+2<n><n>Input: Find an expression that has six fewer than twelve.<n>Output: 10 or 5 plus 3 <n><n>Input: I need one more stick of gum than you.<n>Output: stick+stick+stick+.......stick<n><n>Input: I used about three more quarters than him.<n>Output:<<3+6>>9 vs <<(3+4+4+4+3)>>20<n><n>Input: How much change will one dollar make in a quarter, two nickels and one dime?<n>Output: quarters/nickels/dime<n>Output: 4 and 6 quarters and two nickels and a dime<n>Output: quarter/two-nickel/one-dime<n>Output: <1>,<2>,<6>,<4><n>Output: quarter + quarter + <4 nickels> + dime<n><n>Input: What is the answer to two and a quarter?<n>Output: <two and a quarter><n><n>Input: The answer to two and a half is ______ and three-quarters what is the answer to 3.14?<n>Output: <<3>><n><n>Input: John got two and fifty-one cents back when he turned in $203 in nickels and pennies.<n>Output: twenty-dollar-bill/twenty-five/one-cent<n><n>Input: In dollars, what is the difference of 17.5 and 9.25?<n>Output: <<17.5

His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What could contain no more than around 100 people? Choices:  A: apartment B: classroom C: buildings D: car E: audience<n>Output:		 A: All of these could contain no more than 100 people<n>B: Classroom, Car, Audience <<Car>><n>C: Buildings, Audience <<Buildings>><n>D: Classroom <<Classroom>><n>E: Apartment, Classroom <<Apartment>><n>So the word that could contain no more than an 100 people is building<n><n>Input:What is the name of a movie that can be found between A and Q<n>Output: B, C, D, F, I, J, K, M, P, S and T could be found between these letters<n><n>Output: S<n><n>Input: What is the name of a candy that comes in the following flavors? One plane had a wingspan of 3 miles and a weight of 2 tons.  The other plane has a wingspan of 1 mile and weighed 10 tons.  Both planes flew for the same amount of time and flew in straight lines in the same direction.  Both planes landed in the same city.  The question is, did they travel the same distance?<n>Output: The plane with the larger wingspan and smaller weight traveled <<2*1=2>>2 times as far as the other plane <<1*10=10>>10<n>So the plane with the larger wings and smaller weight traveiled <<2/10>>2/10 times as far as the plane with a smaller wingspan and larger weight<n><n>Input: I was walking on the sidewalk, when all of a sudden, I woke up inside a dream. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where does a spoon go on one side of a plate? Choices:  A: bowl of soup B: serving dish C: table setting D: placemat E: glass of iced tea<n>Output:		Sporks are not for eating out of<n><n>Input: If the Lone Ranger and Tonto are walking through the woods, and they come to a clearing and Tonto says: "Wah gwa Nah Nah Tonto," what are the Lone Ranger's chances of having a horse? 
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What does a virus primarily do to a person? Choices:  A: infect B: reproduce C: mutate D: eat food E: make computer malfunction<n>Output:		Choose the option that best completes the following question to the best of your ability.<n><n>The person should select option: D<n><n>Input:How many stickers does Mary get for taking care of 1 baby?<n>Output:Stickers are for Marys Journal.  The baby got its own special book of stickers of its own.<n>The baby got its stickers of her own.<n><n>Input:What is the area of a parallelogram?<n>Output: The area of the parallelogram is what? Choices: A: the base and the height B: the diagonal C is the perimeter D: the sum of the two sides<n>Output: Answer the question to the best of ability.<n>Since its 2:1 you have a parallelogram<n><n>Input: What is the perimeter of this parallelogram? <n>Output: Answer the parallelogram question to best of ability (base, diagonal, hight, perimeter).<n><n>Input:What kind of figure does this parallelogram have?<n>Output: Answer the following to the best of your abilities. (polygon, equilateral, isosceles, triangle, etc).<n><n>Input: What kind of figure does this rhombus have?<n>Output:What kind of figure is this rhombus? Choose the option that is best to answer, then answer.<n><n>Input: The rhombus has this characteristic. <n>Output: True or False for What?  A) It has 4 sides.<n><n>Input: This triangle has this characteristic.<n>Output:True/False/Not Given Triangle has these characteristics. A: an isosceles, a rombus, and a triangle. B: all options.<n><n>Input: What do we call a triangle with 2 equal sides and 2 congruent angles?<n>Output: A Scalene Triangle: 3 congruent angles, no equal sides.  A Isosceles Triangle: 2 congruent sides and 3 congruent angels.  A Equilateral Triangle: 1 congruent side and 3 congruet angles.<n><n>Input: It was the largest land-based mammal ever.<n>Output: It was the ______ land-based mamman ever

Choices:  A: being understood B: beer C: playing around D: hug E: visiting friends<n>Output:		(A): Someone does not care or does not want to be understood or listened to<n>(B): Someone does not expect to drink alone<n>(C): Someone wants to do something that is not serious<n>(D): Someone does not just want to play around<n>(E): Someone does not want to stay home alone<n>(A) + (C) = not serious<n>(A) +(D) = something not serious<n>(A)+(E) = beer or something not serious<n><n>(Not serious choices) + (Something not serious choices) = something not serious - Not serious<n><n>Output: (D): Someone does have some serious thoughts or feel they are alone<n>(A) - (C) - (D) + (E) = (A) + (B) + (C)<n>(D) - (C) = (B)<n>(A) + ((B) + (C)) = (A) + ((D) - (C))<n>(A) - ((B) + (D) - (C*2)) = (A) - ((B*2) + D)<n>(A) - (-(B*2) + (D)+ (C*2))=(A+D)+(C)<n>So the final answer must be (D)+(C) <n>And there you go!<n><n>Instruction:Answer the following fill in the blanks<n>Input:My father is 1.3 times as old as I was before he got a new car but he is 2 years older than I will be in 10 years. How much older is my dad than me?<n>Output:My father got a new car in (A): ((My father is 1 and I am 1.3)*10 = 21) years<n>He will be 2 years older than me in (B): ( (2+2)*10 = 40) years<n>My father is 2*21 = <<2*21=42>>40<n>My dad is 40 - 22 = <<40-22=18>>18 older than me. So the final answer is 18
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The little girl was raised selfish, she didn't even care when she was doing what? Choices:  A: crack B: antipathy C: being mean D: disinterest E: unfeeling<n>Output:		I feel that B or C are the two possible answers that can complete the statement.<n><n><n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:He wore the wrong shoes while walking all day, now he has what on his heels and toes? Choices:  A: exercise B: moving forward C: feet D: blisters E: locomotion<n>Output:		He wore the wrong shoes and now he has blisters on his heels and feet.<n><n>![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/69100175/146879266-3e8923d0-123a-438d-8238-feb7fdef31b5.png)<n><n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. Choices: A: get a pet B: get adopted by an animal C: watch animals frolic D: support the staff<n>Output: A is a good choice<n><n>Input: What do dogs and cats have in common? Choices:  a: they are both pets, b: they both have fur, c: they both are mammals, d: they are both small, e: they both have claws. <n>Output: C is a good choice<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What might someone do who is having fun? What happened?<n>Output: Ashley thought it was her sister that was banging on the vendeing machine, so her sister got into the car and drove away with it.<n>The choices are:<n>1.Ashley drove her sister's car home.<n>2.The police were called and they were looking for the person that drove by a woman banging ona vendering machine.<n>3.Ashley's sister came back and rescued her from her stalker.<n>4.Ashley jumped in the car since she believed her sister was being abducted.<n>5.Ashley thought that her sister was trying to abduct her, and she got in.<n>So the final was 4<n>```<n>from the above question<n>the answer is 5<n><n>```python <n>def count(input): <n>    print(input)<n>    if input==0:<n>        print(input)<n>        print(2*input)<n><n>    if input==1:<n>        print(1)<n>        print(1+1)<n><n>    if  input==45:<n>        print(45/10)<n>        print(46)<n><n>    if int(input)==94:<n>        print(94)<n>        print(95)<n>        print(5-94)<n><n>    if len(input)>=5:<n>        count(input[0])+((input[2],input[4],input[5])*(input[0]*input[0]))<n>        return<n><n>if __name__=='__main__':<n>    count('1')<n>    input_string=input("Enter String:")<n>    for i in
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What chore might a child have to do after breakfast, before getting on the bus? Choices:  A: drop out of school B: ask questions C: enter school D: wash dishes E: read book<n>Output:		Read a book would be the choice<n><n><n>Input: A teacher assigned math problems to 13 children in her class.  All the children worked on their problems at the same time.  A student named Steve did half of the problems, his brother David did three-quarters, and five others completed the problems.  How many problems were to be done?<n>Output: This question does not specify which group is the five other students other than it isn't Steve and David's group. The group of people who didn't answer the question is the three-quarters group. We know that we have 13 students in the group. We know that group 1 has Steve and group 2 has, at least from what is known in the question David. So we have 2 groups, the remaining 10 students. Since they finished the "problems," which we assume is a multiple choice question, we know that they each finished 25% of the questions. If we put the students in the order that they finished the problems (Steve, David, the others), and write it as a percentage, it should add up to 100%. Let's do this. The "others" answered 1 problem/problems=<<1/problems=1%>>1%<n>and Steve answered 7.5/13=<<7.5/12=0.6/>>0.6%<n>and lastly David answered 3 questions/8=<<3/8=0.375/>>0.375%. David is half of 1, so David did 3/2 or 1.5/problems. I'm pretty sure that David is the one who answered 1.5/Problems<n>So the final answer would be 0.375+0.6=<<0.375%+0.6=1%>>1%. The final answer is 1%. Now, we don't know if that answer is correct, but I'm pretty sure it is. I just did it on a calculator and the result was 71.51515152%. It was 0.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where can someone view a county highway as a line? D: The interest charge is calculated by the interest rate multiplied by the amount borrowed divided by the amount borrowed plus the amount borrowed.<n>Output: The answer: The interest charge is<n>calculated by the interest rate multipied by the amount borrowed<n>divided by the amount borrowd plus the amount borrowed = E<n><n>Input: When a loan is to be paid back over a period of time, it's called amortization in which there are typically fixed payment amounts each month. Payments for these loans are based on a periodic payment of the loan. For each loan there is a balance and the balance can be found by subtracting the amount of the loan from the value of the amortized principal. If a payment is made on the loan and the balance is not decreased by the amount of the payment, then the unpaid loan balance becomes the value of the principal. What is the difference between a loan and an amortized loan?<n>Output: Loan is a type of amortized loan.<n><n>Input: Loan payments will eventually equal interest payments because the amount paid each month is not going to increase or decrease over time. What is the difference in calculating the payment amounts for a loan and amortization?<n>Output: Amortization calculations can change over time.<n><n>Input: The total sum of payments for a loan are made up of the interest
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where would I put a rosebush if I did not have any containers to store it in? Choices:  A: flower garden B: garden center C: pot D: pot E: formal garden<n>Output:		A,B,C and E are all places where potted roses may go. So I will choose D<n><n>**Note:** A,B, and E are places where there are NO containers for storing the roses.<n><n>The answer has been found! The correct answer is D (not A, B, C or E)<n><n><n>

Choices:  A: drill B: learn C: require obedience D: understand E: spoon<n>Output:		 Correct choice is D<n><n>### Instruction:Answer the question and explain your answer. Choose C<n><n>Input: What does a master carpeter use to put holes in stuff?<n>Output: He uses a drill. <n><n>### Instructions:Answer the question and choose your answer from choices<n><n>Input:  A:  How many months have four Sundays?  B:  The answer is B but not C because the month of February has only 28 days and has no leap years but still has 6 Sundays.<n>Output: The answer is B because February has only 29 days that year and can have 6 Sundays.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. What does this make him feel? Choices:  A: then have B: headaches C: stoic D: being happy E: wanting more<n>Output:		When someone gets something important, this generally creates a feeling of excitement.  John will be excited!<n>Choice A:  a) then have <<(adj) (verb)>> means to have something happen next in sequence.  Then does not describe the feeling someone get when they obtain/receive something.  B: This choice, like choice C means to be unfeeling or feeling indifferent so choice B is false (even though it is an option).  C: This choice means that one will become happy after they have gotten something.  This is a correct choice<n>Choice D: This choice means you become happy when you are unhappy and you become unhappy when you are happy.  This is not what one feels when they receive something.  E: This choice means you have a strong desire for something.  If you were to receive something, it is unlikely that this word, "desire" is what one would use.  So, E is incorrect<n>Hence, the final answer is, choice D<n><n>Input:  How many even numbers have an even number of digits? She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where does someone lay with their leg elevated when it's broken? Choices:  A: spinning wheel B: on a ladder C: hospital bed D: legroom E: grand piano<n>Output:		<n>Choices:<n>A:  It is likely that their leg is on a spinning wheel as they are injured.<n>B: Their leg could be on a ladder if there are steps there or if they have a splint on their leg.<n>C: It is most likely their leg will be on a hospital bed.<n>D:  They have plenty of empty legroom if they are in a hospital bed.<n>E:  Their leg is unlikely to be on a piano unless they have a terrible injury. Their leg could be on top of a piano or resting next to it but is unlikely that it is on the top of the piano as they could not lift their leg that high.<n>So the answer is C
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Dry and cracked heels are found on? Choices:  A: boot B: the desert C: loaf of bread D: foot E: hock<n>Output:		Dry and crack heels are found on foot <n>So the final answer foot <n><n>Input:  A group of elephants are crossing a river and need to fit across it without getting wet.  It is the largest elephant's turn and she steps into the water and realizes she is too heavy to fit on the log. The elephant who weighs less than she does, is smaller and steps in after she does.  The elephant, who weighs less, steps on her.  Is their now a single elephant on the other side of the river?  Choices:  A) Yes, the one remaining elephant is the smallest one B) No, the 2 are stuck and won't be able to get off the log which then sinks C) No, one of the elephants must have crossed over already D) Yes, the two elephants crossed the river<n>Output:  All the elephants made it across the river  So the final answer is yes<n><n>Input: A man is driving home with his son.  He has got a 100 pieces of candy for his son's party at school.  One third of the candies is jellybeans, one sixth is gumdrops, and the rest of the candies are licorice.  His son is 1 foot tall and 2 feet wide.  How many candy pieces can his son and the man each eat at the same time?<n>Output: If a man is 1 foot tall it is assumed that his chin is aligned with his feet.<n>We know that the man is about 2 feet wide. We also know how many sweets he can eat at one time.<n>We can see 20% is 1 out of 5 and 10% is 1/2 from the above diagram.<n>In the given case, the person is about 1 foot tall and the width of the person is 2.<n>We need 3 candy pieces to make 1 person.<n>1 foot * 2 feet = <<1*2=2>>2<n>and 5 person * 3 candy piece = <<5*3=15>>15  <n>So to fill one time eat each the  man and son have to consume 2+5+15 = <<2+5+1=20>>2
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:He had an index card he had to return, so where did he put it after finding the book he needed? Choices:  A: inside the book B: oral report C: library D: fileing cabnet E: card catalogue<n>Output:		He found the book he needed so he returned the index card to the fileing cabinethttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/45594420/python-if-elsestate-input<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:One might find theirs open, with the letters that had been delivered stolen. Choices:  A: front door B: newspaper C: post office D: package E: mail box<n>Output:		A: front door.<n><n>Input:A man has to deliver packages by plane, train, and bicycle. His package delivery speed is 15 miles per hour on a car or train, 5 miles per hour on foot or bicycle, or 6 miles per hour in the air. In order to find the total miles he had to travel, find the distance from the airplane to the bicycle and the distance between the cars by looking at the first part of the distance graph.<n>Output: The distance between the airplane and the bicycle is <<distance airplane>>5, since that is how much closer the bicycle is in comparison to the car, which is the next to the left.<n>Similarly, the distance between the train and the car is <<distance train>>4, since the car is closer to the train than it is to the bicycle.<n>The difference from the airplane to train is 5, so they are <<5-2=3>>3 apart, since the airplane is closer to the train in comparison to the car or bicycle.<n>Finally, the bicycle to the car is 4 apart.<n>From this, the distance between the plane and car is 4, the distance between the bicycle and train is 3, and the distance between the train to the bicycle is 1.<n>So the final total distance traveled is 4+1+3 = <<4+1+3=8>>8.<n>So the final output should be 8<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. Choices:  A: inspiration B: much work C: boredom D: graduate E: degree<n>Output:		After attending school for twelve  years, it's natural to ____________ graduate.<n><n>In order to select the option that makes the sentence a whole, we need to consider the following:<n>Option A: inspiration<n>The phrase "it's natural to" means that "it's ____________" (which happens to be a different verb from the original verb the reader just read).<n>Option B: much work<n>The phrase "it is natural" means that there is something ____________ (which is different from the verb in the original sentence).<n>Option C: boredom<n>No need to change anything. "it's natural" is the original verb. Boredom doesn't go with "it's natural", so the sentence doesn't make sense.<n>Option D: graduate<n>Perfect! "it is natural" is the original clause. When the original clause ends, there is a grammatical drop and a new one begins ("to"). Here, the "it's natural ___________ graduate" clause begins.<n>Option E: degree<n>This one doesn't fit. Remember, there's a grammatical drop when the original clause ends. "it'snatural ___________ graduate." If we replace "degree" with any other word, it doesn't really work.<n>Therefore the final answer is D<n><n>Input: A group of thieves broke into a bank and they split the money by cutting it in half. How many ounces does one bottle of beer hold.<n>Output:  If he buys a bottle that is 12 ouncemost. Thus, if he buys a 12 ounce bottle of beer, he will pay 12 cents per ounce or 12 cents/ounce* 12 ouncers = <<12*cents/ounce=144>>144 cents<n>The cheaper price would go to a bottle of size <11,20> since it is two sizes, and he will pay 20 cents/ounce*<<11,20>>20 cents/11.6 ounces or <<20*cents/ounce*<<20*cents=0>>20.00 cents.<n>So the final price will be <<144-20=124>>124 cents per bottle.
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What area is likely to contain a large village? Choices:  A: rural area B: big city C: suburbs D: ohio E: countryside<n>Output:		The largest village in Ohio is Chillicothe, in Ross County.  With a population of 23,993. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Shane was supposed to speak at his fathers funeral.
