How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:She had a knack for entertaining, everybody told he she had a what? Choices:  A: fun B: talent C: learn about D: intelligence E: recognize<n>Output:		She had a talent for<n>She had an Intelligence<n>She had an entertaining talent<n>She had an unusual talent<n>She had a knowhow talent<n>She recognized the talent that she had<n><n>Input:Anne told him if he kept on going at the same speed he would have traveled 300 miles before midnight tonight.   If the distance he traveled so far was in miles and he is currently moving at 50 miles an hour, how many hours did it take him to travel 150 miles?<n>Output:Since it took him 300 miles by midnight, the time taken is 300/50 =<<300/59=5>>.5 hours<n>So time taken is 36 hours for 300/0r 59 = <<36>>36 hours<n>Since he had 150 miles on him while traveling at 50 miles hr, he took 36 * 5 = <<36*5=18>>18 hours to travel 158 miles<n>Since it took him 18 hours for 158 miles, he is therefore moving at a speed of 158/18 = <<158/1=9>>.9 miles per hour or roughly 10 miles per hour<n><n>Input:Ms. Finkelman has a stack of papers to grade.  If every student's answer is marked wrong and every math problem is marked correct, how many papers will she grade incorrectly?<n>Output:She will grade 600 papers by doing this way<n><n>Input:Jesse has a bag of candy, with $1.50 inside.  The candy costs $10, so she only has enough for 6.5 bags. If her dad gave her 10 50-cent pieces, what can she buy with the change?<n>Output:She can buy 2 bags by using this<n>This gives a change of $1.50/0.50 =<< 1.50/5=0.3>> or 30 cents.<n>So, 100-30 cents gives a total of 70 cents.<n>6.5 * 70 = <<6.5*70=457>>457<n>There fore,
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Dave put his beer where he could get to it, but it would be off the floor.  Where did he put it? Choices:  A: refrigerator B: closet C: can D: shelf E: soccer game<n>Output:		Dave put it on the floor because he thought "why not?"<n><n>## Instruction: Please answer each question.<n><n>### Question 1: There are four people on a basketball team: Joe, Carl, Tom and Alice. How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. Choices:  A: go shopping B: generous C: earn money D: have money E: gift buyer<n>Output:		A, B, C, D, E<n>If your choices are A, B, C or D, you would all be known as gift buyers.<n>These are the words we want to find:<n>if (choice.toLowerCase() == 'a') {<n>    return ['go shopping'];<n>} else if (choice.toLower() == 'b'){<n>    return ['generous'];<n>} else if(choice.toLowerCase == 'c'){<n>    return  ['earn money'];<n>} else if((choice.toLowerCase' == d'){<n>    return [];<n>} else  if (choice.to lowerCase() == 'e'){<n>    return [ 'have money', 'gift buyer' ];<n>} else{<n>    return []; <n>}<n>

How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What place would a person go to look at zebras? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. F: Boy G: Girl H: Neither I: Both J: Either<n>Output: The answer appears to either be J, or I; the first sentence is unexplained and the second sentence appears to ask an impossible question, in that if the first sentence had been answered, then the second sentence would have been answered.  The only other potential answer may be H (see below):<n><n>Sentence #1: <B>The boy sat on her bed.</B><n>Sentence #2: <I>Which word describes both the boy as the girl?</I><n>This question seems to require that the question be answered by either a B, G, or H.  2(B), 3(G), 2(H) = 7, which is too many.  The question is asking which word describes both the boy _and_ girl, not either a boy or a girl.  We know from Sentence #1 that there must be a boy.  If we substitute Sentence #1 into Sentence #2, we have <Sentence #1>: <B>The boy...</B>.  We also know that there is a sentence describing the girls as something besides "the boy."  A B can describe either a boy or a girls, so we get <Sentence #2>: <Which word describes _both_ the boy and a _girls?_</I>.  Since Sentence #1 did describe the boy and a girl, it does seem that the solution may fall into either Sentence #1, which has 2(B) + 3(G) = 7 or Sentence #2, which has 7 possibilities, none of which match <B>boy and girl</B>.<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Remembering past successe is likely to cause what? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What corner areas have lots of windows? Choices:  A: wall B: office C: space shuttle D: front door E: tent<n>Output:		Since front door is the opposite of corner, it has no windows<n>For space shuttle, there are at least 0 or more windows since it's supposed to be open.<n>For an office,  you'll need at least 1 window to do anything (like look outside)..<n>For a tent, there're 2 ends  that you need some kind of window<n>For a space shuttle, tent and an office, there's 1 end that requires a window while for a wall, it's 3 ends.<n>So in an office and tent which both have 2 ends, you'll need 2 windows.<n>For a tent and space shuttle which both have 1 end, you'll need only 1 window while for a normal wall which has 3 end, you'll at least 3 or more windows<n>(1+2+4=7)  So the final answer is 7<n><n>Input: How many different 3-digit numbers are there?<n>Output: As far as I can think of there's only one digit to choose for each 3 digit number<n>since that's how we define a number.<n>So there's a total of 100 number of 3 digit numbers<n>

Fatigue doesn't necessarily have anything to do with exercising in general.<n>B: is incorrect. Relaxation is what you want following exercise or perhaps when you're not exercising. Resting, meditating and stretching can help your muscles recover between bouts of exercise.<n>Exercising strengthens your body, and this, in turn, can provide you the energy you need to perform daily activities. Although tiredness may be one side effect of exercise, it is generally beneficial to your health and wellness.<n>C: is incorrect. Tiredness is not a word and it is not synonymous with fatigue.<n>D: is incorrect. Muscle fatigue can occur from overexertion, but this doesn't necessarily happen due to exercise.<n>E: is incorrect. Weight loss is a potential side effect of regular exercise; however, it is not the goal of exercise. While weight loss can be a benefit of regular exercise, doing so can also benefit your heart and even lower the risk of certain types of cancer, to name just a few possible benefits.<n>

Then how many items will be in excess? 0 (zero) one (one) two (two) three (three) more than three (more than three).<n>Output: We will take each item from A, B and then C individually. <n><n>A : A has two times as much as B, so it has twice as many items as B. So A and B combined has <<3>>3 times the amount of items as A has.<n><n>B : B has 4 times as many items as C which combined will have 5 times as many items as <<<<A>>>>>>A combined has.<n><n>C : C has 7 items, so we will have 7*(5/3)=5/3 >>5/3>> times as many items as combined as <<<<A>>>><|>>><|>>><|> combined<n><n>So we need to find the <<<<6>>>>>>6 times total amount of items.<n><n>So to find the amount we will do <<<<6>>>>>6/ <<<5/3>>>>>>5/3 *4 = 4/3/5/3=<<1>>>1/.9+.3=<<.1>>.1.10+.2=<<.3>>.3<n><n>After combining A, B and C they have <<<<54>>>>>54/<<<<.3>>>>>3 total items, the final answer is 54 total items<n><n>input:Which of these is the least number that will make 1/2, 1/4, 1/3 when divided
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. Motels are hotels.<n>		In other words if the reception area is the area in between where you wait to be told you are welcome to the meeting than what are these two parts of the hotel have in common?<n>If you say A and C the law firm and lawyers, then you are right:<n>Lawyers are in law firms, in the conference room. Lawyers work in law firms.<n><n>In law firms and conference rooms, you would get to the conference from the reception area. Lawyers work at law firms. Reception areas are in between the conference room and the law firm. In the conference room is an invitation to work at a law firm.<n><n>If the answer is both C and D the reception area and the conference room.<n>The reception area is the reception area for a motel and a conference room for a law office. What do the reception area and the law offices have in common? The reception areas and the law offices are both parts of these buildings. The reception area is in the building (and the hotel rooms) and the reception area is in the law's office conference room. This also explains the law in the conference room is an opening event for the reception area.<n>If the answer was reception areas and the conference room, then you would also say, "What do reception areas and conference rooms have in common?" The answer is, it is the room in which you have to wait to be told you have to do something. If you use all of these examples together, they all have in common the reception area
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:How would someone feel after going for run? Choices:  A: working out B: sore C: get tired D: satisfaction E: falling down<n>Output:		A: Working out<n><n><n><n><n><n>

If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where can you see a mammoth in NYC? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:How do you indicate that you agree wtih someone? Choices:  A: zoo B: workplace C: sky D: new york city E: many places<n>Output:		A: You can see animals at a zoo B: You can see animals on the job C: You can see animals in the sky and in the clouds  D: You can see animals many times during your life but only around 5-10 minutes at a time  E: You can see animals everywhere in New York!<n><n>### TAKE A QUIZ:<n><n>*https://quizlet.com/_1dk95e#*<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats. The ball is hollow.  Volume of a sphere is determined by the formula: 4/3 * 3.14 * pi * radius cubed  The radius is 2.4 cm * 3.1 cm * 3.0 cm to obtain the volume of 22 cubic cm.<n>So the answer is A 22 0.022 cubic inches.<n><n>input: The number 34 has a factor of 7.  When a pair of numbers have multiple factors in common, one can remove the number from the original group and end up with the same number.  Which of these numbers cannot be reduced to the number 34?  Choices:  A) 16 B) 19 C) 20 D) 99<n>Output: 34 can be reduced to either 11 or 9.  Since we know the factor of 34 is 7, any number divisible by 7 will also end up with 11 or 7, and since B is not divisible by 7, B cannot be reduced to 34<n>

His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The man was eating lunch, but rushed when he looked at his watch, why did he rush? Choices:  A: gain weight B: late for work C: heartburn D: bad breath E: early for work<n>Output:		He was rushing because he had a bad breath.<n><n>### 2.2 Difficulty:2 Questions<n><n>Input: Choices:  A) he had to meet the president B) his phone went off while he was eating lunch C) he wasn't feeling well D) his work schedule changed E)he heard a noise outside<n>Output:He was doing a meeting with the president.<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>####1.  Answer: A<n><n><n><n>####2. Answer: B<n><n><n><n>####3. Answer: E<n><n><n>## Questions and Answers<n><n>### 1.2, How many hours does each of the below items take?<n><n>|Action| Time (Mins) |<n>|:---:|:---:|<n>|Mowing grass| 40 |<n>|Gaming| 25|<n>|Wash the dishes| 15|<n>|Shower| 20|<n>|Reading| 30|<n>|Work| 35|<n>|Watching television| 35|
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The body guard was good at his duties, he made the person who hired him what? Choices:  A: better job B: irritated C: feel safe D: save money E: headache<n>Output:		The person could be happier than if he did not hire a body guard in the first place. If the body guard failed to do his job, the person would likely have been harmed in some way.<n>So the final choice would be Choices: A<n><n>Input: I am thinking about playing a trick for Halloween but my friends don't want me to play a trick. He didn't like the idea of going outside at all.<n>So the final the guy who was scardiest<n><n>Input: The first person who was scared to go out of a cave, was  ___? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:John and James spent most of their time communicating with each other on their project.  The time required to communicate slowed their what? Choices:  A: static B: train of thought. C: progress D: transfer of information E: collaboration<n>Output:		After they spoke, they slowed down their progress.<n>The only word that fits in context is Slowed. So choose progress<n><n>Input:The number of stamps in the jar decreased by six to 19.  The following is a diagram showing the initial conditions and the change in the number of stamps: Choices: A: 10 -> 9, B: 10 ->5, C: 8 ->5, D: 16 ->9.<n>Output: In this diagram, we can see when they start the diagram with ten stamps and end with five stamps<n><n>Input: There are four kinds of people: cat, shark, otter, and elephant.  Each person types an animal that they think best describes their personality.  Three people choose dog, the fourth person chooses cat and they are each told what animal their choice best represents.  Which of these types of people do not learn anything new? Choice: A: Shark, B: Otter, C: Cat, D: The first<n>Output: Sharks don't learn anything new because no one knows that they are sharks<n><n>Input: Samantha is going on a trip to visit her grandparents in Arizona.  She has 40 miles to make it to the airport and then 1,000 miles to her grandparents' house.  In 21 miles she runs out of gas.  One of her uncles arrives just after her car gives out. How far is her grandparents' place from the airport, assuming that gas stations are evenly distributed on the route?<n>Output: 40+21=61<n>Her grandparents are 1,001 miles away from her airport, so her grandparents are 61 miles into her route<n><n>Input:In each group, there are nine members.  Each student has lunch with the one to his or her left.  One student in each group stays home for lunch.  On the next day, each student has lunch with someone to his left, and the remaining one stays home for lunch again.  What is the next person in each group? Choice: A. the one who started at home the first day<n>Output: The next person in each group is:<n>1st person: The 13rd person<n>2nd person

He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:She loved buying products, she was driven by her what to shop more than any practical needs? She is spending more time shopping and less money.<n>So the final choice that makes sense is A: desire <n><n>Input:The car broke down, so she had to ride the bus.<n>Output: Ride the bus = The bus is going to ride her.   <n><n>Input:The pig got in to trouble for eating dirty food.<n>Output: Ate dirty food = The pig is eating dirty food.   <n><n>Input:"Who made that?"  "I did."      Input: 1) Whose phone is it? 2) What kind of phone is it?<n>Output:1) Whose phone it is= <<Whose=The phone belongs to>> The phone belongs to him.<n>2) What kind of= <<What kind=What type of>> type of phone is it=  It is a new phone

Convert the answer to pounds.  Divide by 16 to get ounces per pound.  For the next step, multiply the number of ounces in an eighth pound by 5.  Divide by the answer from the first step to get ounces in a quarter pound.  Multiply the number of ouncers in a quarter pound by 3.  Divide by four to get ouncers per pound.<n> Output: 16 * 8 = 128 ounces in an 8 ounces. 128/5 = 26 ounces in a pound.<n> 8 ounces in a half pound.<n> 4*8 = 32 ounces in whole pound.<n> 32/26 = 1.244

If you are correct you double your guess and lose everything else.  If you are incorrect, you lose half of your guess and double your guess.  If you can get to a 50/50 situation,  how many guesses do you need to lose all your money?<n>Output: We can see that each guess starts with a 50/49 chance of winning and the next guess starts 50/51 chance of wining and so on <n>And since the 51/51 or 1:2, 1:3 and 1:4 are the only remaining chances, this is the scenario<n>51/51=1:2<n>51/50=1:4<n>50/51=1<n>50/49=2<n><n>and since 50/48 = 1:2<n>50/47 = 1:4<n>51/47 = 2:4<n>52/47 = 4:6<n>53/47 = 9:10<n><n>And the 6th guess must be at least the 9:10 scenario, so we can say at least it is 47:47<n><n>And then the 7:7 scenario (since the 6th guess is not at the 9:11 level) would be at least the 7th guess.<n>We can continue with the 7:5, 7:6, 7:10, and 7:11 scenarios.<n><n>Since the 7:11 requires 47/46 guesses, it cannot fail on the 47:46.<n><n>So 7:11 + 3 scenarios in total, 8:12, 8:13, 8:16, 8:17, 8:18, 8:19
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:She was sick and staying in bed the day of the event, unfortunately this meant she was what? How many prizes was given away?<n>Output: This problem can be rewritten as the scientist with the highest or no one had the highestscore<n>So we have 5 + (1*x) = <<5+x=6>>6<n>If (1*x) can be written as 5/2, 5/3, etc....this says that when x is an integer, how many prizes did the person with the second highest score get?<n>Output: If x=number of prizes then, 5 - (1*x) -------------(1)*(x-1)<n>So, if x=6 5 - (1 *6) ------------- 1*(6-1) <n>So, 5 - (6) ------------- 5-6 <n>So, 0 ------------- 0 <n>(1)*(6-1) ------------- 0<n>So, 0 + 0 = 0<n><n>Input: Everyone at the science expo answered a trivia question to become a contestant. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What's it called when you have seen something through an eyepiece? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where are there more telephone booths? Choices:  A: gas stations B: city C: london D: train station E: airport<n>Output:		There are lots of telephone booths in airports.  If you add up Choices A + Choice B, you get airport, but this option is incorrect because you need to choose an option that has the maximum number of telephone booth.  It would be better to say, If you add up Choice [B: city], you get airport because you get more telephone booth options in the city than any other option<n><n>Input:  There is a pile of rocks behind Alice's house. The rocks are either red or square. The total amount of square rocks in the pile is a power. The square root of 130. The square root of this number is 1.  If there are twice as many red rocks than square rocks, then how many other red rocks are there?<n>Output: If you multiply the square factor 2, you'll get 2 times the number of red rocks 2 x 130 = 260, which isn't the same number.<n>Instead, we can add the number of red rocks to the number for the factor and we'll get the root of the square root 1. So, 130+1 = 131 131 is the largest number that can be divided by 2 to yield no remainder.<n><n>Input:  30 boys went to the school trip.<n>Then 3 times the number of boys went to a new town to visit their grandma.<n>Now 6 times the number of boys left with the 20 teachers to watch a football game.<n>Now 2 times the number stayed behind.<n>How many boys are left?<n>Output: There are 13 boys left, because there are 3 + 3x(number of boys) + 6x(number of boys)+ 2 = 33, so 33+2 = 35 then 35%2 = 13.5, the closest whole number is 13.<n><n>Input:  If I have 26 apples and 18 oranges, how many pairs of fruit do I have?<n>Output: if you have 26 appls and 18 orans, then if you subtract 18 from 26, you'll get the number of pairs. 26-18 = 8<n>Then you can multiply
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:How might a person address someone who is leaving? Choices:  A: further cause B: wave goodbye C: attempt suicide D: insulting them E: thank god<n>Output:		Goodbye<n>I'm sorry for having to leave.<n>I'm looking forward to the future and the new adventures I'll find in this new place.<n>Goodbye!<n><n># Solution:<n># https://github.com/JonathanH/leetcode-solutions-Python<n>import heapq<n><n>class Solution(object):<n>    def singleNumber(self, nums):<n>        """<n>        :type nums: List[int]<n>        :rtype: int<n>        """<n>        nums.sort()<n>        count = 2<n>        for num in nums:<n>            if num == 0:<n>                return num<n>            elif (num - count) % (count + 1) == 0:<n>              # print(str(nums) + " " + str(num - count) + " " +str(num - num % count))<n>                return num - count<n>            heapq.heapify(nums)<n>            count += 1<n>        return 0<n><n>if __name__ == "__main__":<n>    nums = [6,3,2,5,7,0,1,9]<n>    answer = Solution()<n>    print(answer.singleNumber(nums))
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Someone lacking immortality will one day be? Choices:  A: kick the bucket B: mortal C: dead D: can die E: dying<n>Output:		Kick the bucket has nothing to do with immortality, so is not the right answer.<n>Dead is the correct answer<n>

Choices:  A: helicopter B: own cars C: speak words D: believe in god E: dance together<n>Output:		A, B, C<n>So the final answer must be A+B+C = <A+B+C=>><n>A: helicopter<n>B: own cars<n>C: speak words<n>D: believe in god<n>E: dance together<n>Since most people transport themselves, they must have access to the ability to transport themselves.  Transporting themselves involves some combination of A, B, C, D and E. The only combinations that involve a single one of A, B,... E are A, B, C and A, B, E.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:If an animal is tired, what is it likely to do? Choices:  A: burned B: polished C: carved D: composted E: nailed<n>Output:		The only things the letter A, B, C, D&E represents are the  different states of a piece of wood. Let say B for now.  If you want to see your reflection "bought" a mirror and nailed it to the board (state nailed). If you carve B into your board (state carved) you will see your reflection (you can have a mirror and still carve B into the board). Your reflection is your reflection, which is a one-to-one mapping. So, if you are looking in a mirror, you see your reflection. If you are looking in B and are going to turn your head left then right you will see the reflection of your head turning left and right (seeing the reflection of your reflection).<n>The answer to the question is B and D.<n><n><n><n>Input: Alice had 48 hours of free time in January and 36 hours free time in February and she spent them in the following order:<n>8th through 12th with her family outside of San Francisco<n>25th on a day trip to San Francisco<n>13th through 20th volunteering at a local hospital<n>1st and 2nd at a conference in Los Angeles<n>3rd through 5th a friends wedding<n>4th through 6th camping with her family<n>19th through 23rd in Los Angeles for a concert<n>24th through 26th visiting with family<n>15th to 17th at the beach in San Diego<n>18th through 21st at home<n>30th through 31st with friends<n>She added up the time spent <n>with friends in San Diego +  the time spent with family in San Francisco + with friends = 29+34 = <<29+34=63>>63<n><n>This was 1 more than she added in the beginning so the final answer is 28.<n><n><n>

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:If I want to maximize my number of potential customers, where should I build a new department store? Choices:  A: idaho B: shopping mall C: big city D: in town E: new york<n>Output:		If we look at new york first, we have 1+2+3+4+4+7 = <<1+2+3=11:1+4=5>>5/3<n>If we look at in town, we have 1 + 2 + 3 + 8 + 9 + 11 = <<1+2=3:1+8+9+11=20:1+2=22>>22/3<n>If we add in the big city, we have 11+5 = <<11+5=16>>16/3 which is greater than 22/3<n>So the final answer will be big city<n><n>Input: The length of this string is 48, plus 3 times the number of 0's in this string plus 1.  If the substring between positions 0 and 28 is the string a, what is the value of length?<n>Output: Length starts at 48<n>At this point, we only have one 0 "b" so it's 48 + 3*1 = <<48+3*1=51>>51/3<n>In the next 5 chars, we have 0's 0,1,1,2,2,3,3 so 51+5*3 = <<51+5*5=100>>100/3<n>The length ends at 100<n><n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:The dog ran to the front window and barked, this is because of a presence at the what? Choices:  A: building B: friend's house C: classroom D: window E: front door<n>Output:		The dog barked because of a presence at a building<n><n>Answer 1<n>Answer 2<n>Answer 3<n>Answer 4<n><n>Output: Answer 3<n><n>Input: The answer to this question is: <<3*3=9>>9<n><n>Output: <<3*3="9">>The answer to this question is 9<n><n>Answer:<n>Input:The answer to this question has 6 letters: A, B, E, L, P, and T<n><n>Output:The answer to this quiz has 6 letters: <<A,B,E,L,P,T>>A, B, E,L, P,T<n><n>Input: The total of 8.34% is: <<8.34>>.34%<n><n>Output: The total of a tenth of a percent is: <<8.0/10>>.0/10%<n><n>Input: You are the parent of a 2-year-old toddler.  After 3 days, 2 meals, and 1 snack of food, the ratio of the number of calories eaten to the initial number of calories in the food becomes 4/5.  How many calories are in the food initially?<n>Answer: << 4/5, 1/5, 3/5>><n><n>Input: <<A>> 7, <<B>> 10, <<C>> 4, <<D>> 2<n>A+B=<<7+10=17>>17<n>A+C=<<7+4=11>>11<n>A+D=<<7+2=9>>9<n>B+C=<<10+4=14>>1<n>B+D=<<10+2=12>>2<n>C+D=<<4+2=6>>6<n>Therefore, using cross multiplication,<n>17XC+11XD=<<17xC+11xD=18X2>>24<n>2XD+6XC=<<2XD+12X9>>18<n>22XD+24XC=<<22XD+18XC=42X2>>44<n>42X6=<<42x6=252>>25

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn. It seemed like the guys there did nothing but what? Choices:  A: dance B: getting drunk C: meet new people D: having fun E: have fun<n>Output:		 The guys were having fun.  They were dancing, getting drunk, meeting new people, and having fun.  If we use the letters A-F to stand for the choices above,  and A=<<A=1>>1, B=<<B=2>>2, C=<<C=3>>3, D=<<D=4>>4,  E=<<E=5>>5 and F=<<F=6>>6<n>Jimmy didn' think it was any of the options because he has a 5 year old daughter and doesn't drink beer.<n>So the final choice is 5 which represents E=<<E=1>>1<n>So the final answer to this question is E<n><n>Input:There is a group of 4 bachelors that want to pick a date for a night out on the town.  If a bachelor has a birthday in every month which month is he most likely to propose marriage?<n>Output: Let's imagine all 4 are born in January, April, July, October so they'll have a March, June, September, and December birthday.<n>So the answer is 6!B<n>So we start at 1 and multiply each number by the previous number until we end at 6 (the answer)!<n>1X0=0(we start at number 1)<n>2X1=2(we have 2)<n>3X2=6(we have 3 birthdays)<n>4X3=12(we have 4 birthdays)<n>5X4=20(we have 5 birthdays)(6 will have 6)<n>6X5=30(we have 6 birthdays)<n>6X6=36(we have 6)<n>36!/6=6!B<n>So the final answer for this question is 6!B which is equal to 6, 6, 6 or in scientific notation:1/6!2<n><n>Input: What are the next 2 numbers in 10, 15, 20, 16, 115,?<n>Output: We start with 10, 20, we add 10 to both numbers: (10,20)<n>Now we subtract the smaller number from bigger number: (10,80)<n>Now we go

If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What is a sign that you might not be living soon? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where is known to always have snow? Choices:  A: africa B: north pole C: roof D: canada E: surface of earth<n>Output:		The only place that it snows in north is the North Pole. The only place that it rains in south is the southern hemisphere.<n><n>

If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What might someone want to be if he or she is thick? Choices:  A: slender B: free flowing C: sparse D: unacquainted E: diet<n>Output:		We might have taken a guess at slender, free flowing, or unacquainted, but the answer is actually D:  What A thick person would want is to be slender, and therefore the answer is diet<n><n>Input:There are three kinds of tough:  A tough, B tough, and C tough.  Which kind of tough has the most muscles?  Choices: A) A  B) B  C) C  D) C has the most muscles<n>Output: The answer is C:  A tough and a B tough have the same amount of muscles, while the muscle counts are different for each subcategory of A, B, or C. So the only ones with the most muscles are C.

### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:Where could you find a fox hunting when not in a forest? Choices:  A: open meadow B: arctic tundra C: beach D: great outdoors E: england<n>Output:		In a great outdoors. (Since this is not a forest)<n><n>Input: What fruit is spelled with 10 letters? Choices: a: 5 b: 2 c: 9 d: 92 e: 6<n><n>Output: 5 (100% correct with a letter: e)<n><n>Input: Choose an acceptable plural for the word moth. Which gear would have to be in R for the engine to turn freely? How many gears would you have in neutral?  The gear shift has 4 positions. The first position will be labeled 'P', the second 'R' the third 'M', the final 'L'.  'P' stands for parking, 'R' for reverse, 'M' for mid, and 'L' for low.<n><n>Output: First, in order for the engine to turn, it has to be in R.  Since it's a standard transmission, you need to push R to reverse the car, and then shift into neutral.  Once in neutral, it can turn.  You wouldn't have to turn the wheels, as it is a manual transmission, you just have to reverse the car into neutral.  You could have 3 gears in neutral

These are A, B and E<n>So we can take part in A, B and E  If we take part in C,D and F we might accidentally be very talkative, think mean thoughts and spend lots of time online which also prevents us from being around people and being very talkative<n>So we can take one or multiple of A, B, E and F and still be kind<n>If we only take one, we might still be kind but we might not always talk or think mean things or we might not always follow the rules<n>The answer here would be to take part in C which is to be selfish and greedy which is kind of like being mean<n>The answer is C<n>Input: If you are tired and rest, you might feel: Choices: A: sad B: hungry C: bored D: energetic E: energetic<n>Output: The opposite answers for being energetic A, energetic D and tired E are sad B, hungry C and bored D for your physical emotions<n>If you feel bored when you are tired your emotions are bored, not energetic<n>Since your emotions can't be energetic E, energetic D or energetic A, the answer is the emotion that you are not and this is bored C<n>Input:If you are excited and rest, you might  A: feel confused B: feel happy C:
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What is a lover likely to want to do with their partner? Choices:  A: build family together B: fall in love C: make love D: complete E: distance themselves<n>Output:		<n><n>Input: How many letters are in the word ADOPTION? A. 6 B. 7 C. 8 D. 9 E. 10<n>Output: There are 8 unique letters in the word ADOPTEION.<n><n>Input: Jump a 10-legged spider.  A spider typically has eight legs.  It jumps an even number of times because it doubles its legs.  How many jumps does the spider make? (Note: Even if you had a 9-legged spider the answer is not 15.)<n>Output: If the spider doubles its number of legs each time, it starts by having 8 legs and does not have 9 legs ever, so 6 jumps.<n><n>Input: Aaron made a circle and put $10 inside.  He made it into an 8-piece puzzle.  To solve it, he got a different amount of money from each puzzle piece. How much did he get from each one?<n>Output: Everywhere there is <<10*8=80>><>80<n>And the same amount is in <<each>><>. This leaves 80-<<80-1=79>>79<n><n>Input: The largest number of people to attend the worlds largest wedding was in 2008 at a whopping <<16,000+16,001=8,501,613>>8,501.613 people.<n><n>Input: The Worlds Largest Piece Of Ice was 5 times the length and 1 and a half times the width of the worlds largest piece of cheese<n>Output: The largest cheese in the world is 4.2 meters long, 4.8 meters tall, and 2.3 meters<n><n>### Solution:<n><n>First question<n>Mary had 89 stickets. She used 3 large sticker on the front page of the her journal and 7 sticker each to 6 other page. How many sticker does Mary have remaining? ### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100.  His weekly allowance is $5.  His parent will pay him an extra $10 to mow the lawn.  His neighbor will pay him $7 per hour to babysit their son.  He has already saved up $65.  He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What does a person looking for new things in life do? Choices:  A: become depressed B: welcome change C: thank god D: experiences E: pay bills<n>Output:		The person who chooses A chooses B. The person who chooses B is happy that they have no worries of new debt and looks forward for things to come.<n>The person who chooses C is happy that they have all they need, they look for no more things, and it's nice to not have stress of paying bills.<n>The person who has D does not need anything else.<n>The person who would select E chooses C<n>So the answer is D<n><n>Input: What is one good thing about the internet?<n>Output: One thing is you can do a lot of things on the internet. Search for news, facts, and entertainment. Another good thing about the internet is you can make new friends online and also communicate with people who live close to you. <n><n>### Instruction:What does 175+ 147 =?<n><n>Output: 175 is the sum of 1 and 7 and 5 is the sum of the two answers. 1+7=8. 5+4=9 <n>Adding two numbers we get 9; the total of 154 is 9; the sum of the two numbers is also 75+75 and their sum is 175.<n><n>### Instructions:What's the smallest number that is divisible by 54 60 173 and 208?<n><n>Output: 21, because 21 is the square of 4 and square of 4 is 16. 21 - 16 =  5, and 5+1 = 6 which is divisible by all the numbers given<n>
### Instruction:Answer the following multiple choice question.<n><n>Input: Mary had 89 stickers.  She used 3 large stickers on the front page of her journal and 7 stickers each to 6 other pages of her journal. How many stickers does Mary have remaining?<n>Output: Mary added a total of 7 stickers/page * 6 pages= <<7*6=42>>42 stickers to the 6 other pages.<n>In total, Mary added 3 large stickers + 42 stickers = <<3+42=45>>45 stickers to her journal.<n>Since she started with 89 stickers, she now has 89 - 45 = <<89-45=44>>44 stickers left.<n>So the final answer is 44<n><n>Input: Zach is saving his money to buy a brand new bike that costs $100. He'll receive his allowance on Friday and he's planning on babysitting for 2 hours this Saturday after he mows the lawn.  How much more money does Zach need to earn before he can buy the bike?<n>Output: If he babysits for 2 hours at $7 per hour, he will earn 2*7 = $<<2*7=14>>14<n>This week he will earn $5 allowance, $10 mowing the lawn and $14 from babysitting for a total of 5+10+14 = $<<5+10+14=29>>29<n>If we add the $29 he will earn to his $65 savings, he will have a total of 29 + 65 = $<<29+65=94>>94<n>The bike costs $100 and he will have $94 leaving $100-$94 = $<<100-94=6>>6 more that he will need to earn<n>So the final answer is 6<n><n>Input: Mark has kangaroos and goats.  Kangaroos have two legs and goats have four legs.  If he has 23 kangaroos and three times as many goats as kangaroos what is the total number of legs of all his animals?<n>Output: His kangaroos have a total of 23*2=<<23*2=46>>46 legs<n>He has 23*3=<<23*3=69>>69 goats<n>The goats have 69*4=<<69*4=276>>276 legs<n>So in total his animals have 276+46=<<276+46=322>>322 legs<n>So the final answer is 322<n><n>Input:What often happens after a long day of traveling? Choices: forrest A ocean B grassland C desert D coral reef<n>Output: desert is not an ecosysem, as ecosystem must include many organisms<n><n>###### Hint 1<n>The choices you have is 'A forest, Ocean, grassland & desert' and only one of the choices is false because deserts does not include many organisms<n>###### Hint2 -<n>The organisms that is present in the desert is not many<n>
